"# Chapter 1 — Propositional Logic in Motoi Scheme

Where we start with the smallest possible logic: a light switch and its friends.

I want to open this book by promising you very little. Propositional logic is
narrow. It cannot say *every*, it cannot say *some*, it cannot talk about
particular things at all. It talks about statements as wholes and about how
those statements combine. That is it. That is the whole starting move, and I
am going to spend a chapter on it because everything that follows in this
book climbs on top of it. If the ladder is loose at the bottom, the top of
the ladder is nowhere.

A propositional statement is a claim you could look at and decide, in
principle, whether it is true or false. *The sky is grey.* *You are reading
this book.* *Seven is prime.* Each of these has a truth value. I do not need
to know which value. I just need to know that there is one, and that it is
either true or false — nothing in between, for now. (In chapter 14 we will
loosen the *nothing in between* part. Let it stand for the moment.)

We are going to teach the Scheme runtime how to hold such statements and how
to combine them. And because we are Scheme people, we will do it with lists
and pattern-matching, not with special new syntax.

> **the runtime says**
>
> *When someone asks me what logic actually is, I usually say: logic is what
> stays true when you forget what you were talking about. A statement about
> a bird and a statement about a stock and a statement about a proof all
> obey the same rules of combination. Propositional logic is those rules,
> stripped down to their smallest form.*

## The pieces on the table

Five moves. That is what propositional logic gives you. You can:

1. **Assert** a proposition. *P.*
2. **Negate** it. *not P.*
3. **Conjoin** two. *P and Q.*
4. **Disjoin** two. *P or Q.*
5. **Imply**. *if P then Q.*

Some textbooks add *if and only if* as a sixth. It is a shorthand — *P iff Q*
is exactly *(P implies Q) and (Q implies P)* — but it is such a useful
shorthand that it deserves the seat. So call it six.

These are called *connectives*. The symbols vary by book — mathematicians
love the little wedges and hooks — but in Scheme we can just spell them
plainly.

```scheme
;; A proposition is a symbol or one of these compound forms.
;;   'P                                     ; atomic
;;   (list 'not p)                          ; negation
;;   (list 'and p q)                        ; conjunction
;;   (list 'or  p q)                        ; disjunction
;;   (list 'implies p q)                    ; implication
;;   (list 'iff     p q)                    ; biconditional
```

That is our little abstract syntax tree. Notice we did not invent a new type;
we used the humblest thing Scheme has, the list. The head of the list is the
connective, and the tail is the arguments. Anything that starts with `and`
is a conjunction. Anything with no list wrapper at all — a bare symbol — is
an atomic proposition.

## An interpreter

The next thing we need is a way to *evaluate* one of these lists against a
world in which each atomic proposition has been given a truth value. Call
that a *valuation*: a mapping from atomic-proposition names to booleans.

```scheme
;; A valuation is a list of pairs: '((P . #t) (Q . #f) (R . #t))

(define (lookup name valuation)
  ;; Find the truth value of an atomic proposition in a valuation.
  (let ((pair (assq name valuation)))
    (if pair
        (cdr pair)
        (error \"unknown proposition\" name))))

(define (eval-prop expr valuation)
  ;; The interpreter. One line per connective.
  (cond
    ((symbol? expr)
     (lookup expr valuation))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'not)
     (not (eval-prop (cadr expr) valuation)))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'and)
     (and (eval-prop (cadr expr) valuation)
          (eval-prop (caddr expr) valuation)))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'or)
     (or  (eval-prop (cadr expr) valuation)
          (eval-prop (caddr expr) valuation)))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'implies)
     ;; P → Q is equivalent to (not P) ∨ Q
     (or (not (eval-prop (cadr expr) valuation))
         (eval-prop (caddr expr) valuation)))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'iff)
     (eq? (eval-prop (cadr expr)  valuation)
          (eval-prop (caddr expr) valuation)))
    (else
     (error \"unknown form\" expr))))
```

Line by line. `lookup` walks the valuation list until it finds the pair whose
`car` matches the name. `assq` is the Scheme primitive that does association
lookup by `eq?`, which is what we want for symbols. If the atomic
proposition is not in the valuation at all, we do not silently return `#f` —
we raise an error. Silently returning `#f` would be dishonest. If you ask me
whether an unknown proposition is true, the answer is neither *yes* nor *no*
but *I do not know what you are asking about*, and that is what the error
communicates.

The interpreter has one arm per connective. Negation flips. Conjunction is
the runtime `and`. Disjunction is the runtime `or`. Implication is defined
in terms of negation and disjunction — this is the *material conditional*
convention, which we will come back to in chapter 7 when we discover it
sits uneasily with how humans actually reason. Biconditional is a same-truth
check.

Try it.

```scheme
(eval-prop '(and P Q)
           '((P . #t) (Q . #f)))
;; => #f

(eval-prop '(or (not P) Q)
           '((P . #t) (Q . #t)))
;; => #t

(eval-prop '(implies (and P (not Q)) R)
           '((P . #t) (Q . #f) (R . #t)))
;; => #t
```

That last one deserves a moment. *If P and not Q, then R.* The valuation says
P is true, Q is false, so *P and not Q* is true. R is true. Truth implies
truth, so the whole thing is true.

## Truth tables

The classical way to survey a propositional formula is to enumerate all
possible valuations and see when the formula is true. That is a *truth
table*. Let us build one.

```scheme
(define (collect-atoms expr)
  ;; Walk the AST and collect all atomic-proposition symbols, no duplicates.
  (cond
    ((symbol? expr) (list expr))
    (else
     (let ((connective (car expr))
           (args       (cdr expr)))
       (dedupe (apply append (map collect-atoms args)))))))

(define (dedupe xs)
  ;; Remove duplicates, preserving first-seen order.
  (if (null? xs)
      '()
      (cons (car xs)
            (dedupe (filter (lambda (x) (not (eq? x (car xs))))
                            (cdr xs))))))
```

`collect-atoms` recurses into the tree; when it hits a bare symbol, it wraps
it in a singleton list, and when it hits a compound form it collects atoms
from every argument and appends them. `dedupe` walks the resulting list and
keeps only the first occurrence of each symbol. We use `filter`, which is a
core verb, to drop later occurrences.

Now the enumeration. Given *n* atoms, we produce all 2^n valuations.

```scheme
(define (all-valuations atoms)
  (if (null? atoms)
      (list '())                       ; one valuation: the empty one
      (let ((rest (all-valuations (cdr atoms))))
        (append
          (map (lambda (v) (cons (cons (car atoms) #t) v)) rest)
          (map (lambda (v) (cons (cons (car atoms) #f) v)) rest)))))
```

Read that recursion carefully. If there are no atoms, there is exactly one
valuation, the empty one. Otherwise, recur on the tail to get all
valuations over the remaining atoms; then double the result, once with the
head atom bound to `#t` and once with it bound to `#f`.

The truth table itself:

```scheme
(define (truth-table expr)
  (let ((atoms (collect-atoms expr)))
    (map (lambda (val)
           (cons val (eval-prop expr val)))
         (all-valuations atoms))))

(truth-table '(implies P Q))
;; => (
;;      (((P . #t) (Q . #t)) . #t)
;;      (((P . #t) (Q . #f)) . #f)
;;      (((P . #f) (Q . #t)) . #t)
;;      (((P . #f) (Q . #f)) . #t)
;;    )
```

There is the notorious row: *P false, Q false, therefore P implies Q is
true.* People trip on this constantly. The intuition: an implication only
lies when the antecedent holds and the conclusion fails. If the antecedent
does not hold, the implication was never called on to say anything, so we
grant it truth by default. This is called *vacuous truth*, and I mention it
here because you will meet it again in every chapter of this book that
touches proof.

## Tautology, contradiction, contingency

Three vocabulary words. A *tautology* is a formula that is true in every
valuation. A *contradiction* is a formula that is false in every valuation.
A *contingency* is anything else — sometimes true, sometimes false.

```scheme
(define (tautology? expr)
  (every (lambda (row) (cdr row))
         (truth-table expr)))

(define (contradiction? expr)
  (every (lambda (row) (not (cdr row))))
         (truth-table expr))

(define (contingent? expr)
  (and (not (tautology?    expr))
       (not (contradiction? expr))))
```

`every` is the fold-over-a-boolean core verb; it returns `#t` when the
predicate holds for every element of the list, `#f` otherwise. So a
tautology is a formula whose truth-table rows are all true, a contradiction
is one whose rows are all false, and a contingent formula is neither.

Some classic tautologies.

```scheme
(tautology? '(or P (not P)))                          ; => #t   ; excluded middle
(tautology? '(implies (implies P Q)
                      (implies (not Q) (not P))))    ; => #t   ; contrapositive
(tautology? '(implies (and (implies P Q) P) Q))      ; => #t   ; modus ponens

(contradiction? '(and P (not P)))                    ; => #t   ; contradiction
```

The law of the excluded middle — *P or not-P* — is the one you were probably
taught first as a schoolchild, if you were taught this at all. It says that
a statement is either true or its negation is; there is no third option.
Aristotle wrote about this; it survived unchallenged for two millennia. In
chapter 7 we will meet a logic that gives it up. That will feel destabilising
the first time; it is worth it.

Modus ponens is the reasoning move that says *if I know P implies Q, and I
know P, then I know Q.* It is the workhorse of every proof you have ever
read. It should feel obvious. The truth-table check confirms it.

## Semantic entailment

We now have enough to say what it means for a formula to *follow from* a set
of formulas. This is the notion at the heart of logic. We write

    Γ ⊨ φ

and read it *Γ entails φ*. Semantically: every valuation that makes every
formula in Γ true also makes φ true. There is no way to satisfy Γ without
also satisfying φ.

```scheme
(define (entails? premises conclusion)
  ;; True if every valuation satisfying all premises also satisfies conclusion.
  (let* ((atoms (dedupe (apply append
                               (map collect-atoms
                                    (cons conclusion premises))))))
    (every (lambda (val)
             (if (every (lambda (p) (eval-prop p val)) premises)
                 (eval-prop conclusion val)
                 #t))                            ; vacuous
           (all-valuations atoms))))

(entails? '((implies P Q) P) 'Q)                  ; => #t   ; modus ponens
(entails? '((or P Q) (not P)) 'Q)                 ; => #t   ; disjunctive syllogism
(entails? '((implies P Q)) '(implies Q P))        ; => #f   ; NOT contrapositive
```

The third example is important. From *P implies Q* you may not conclude
*Q implies P*. Called *affirming the consequent*, it is one of the two most
common fallacies people commit in real reasoning. (The other is *denying the
antecedent*: from *P implies Q* and *not P*, one may not conclude *not Q*.)
Our little checker catches both, and I encourage you to convince yourself by
running the truth tables by hand.

## Normal forms

There is a well-known fact about propositional logic: any formula can be
rewritten so that it consists only of negations, conjunctions, and
disjunctions, arranged in a particular shape. Two shapes matter enough to
have names:

- **Conjunctive Normal Form (CNF)**: a big *and* of *ors of literals*.
- **Disjunctive Normal Form (DNF)**: a big *or*  of *ands of literals*.

A *literal* is either an atomic proposition or its negation.

Why care? Because algorithms that answer questions about propositional
formulas — is this satisfiable? is this a tautology? — are much easier to
express when the formula is in one of these shapes. In particular, CNF is
the input format for *SAT solvers*, which we will meet in Appendix D.

Converting to CNF has three phases:

1. Eliminate implications and biconditionals in favour of and/or/not.
2. Push negations inward until they sit only on atoms (De Morgan's laws).
3. Distribute disjunctions over conjunctions.

Here is the first phase.

```scheme
(define (eliminate-implications expr)
  (cond
    ((symbol? expr) expr)
    ((eq? (car expr) 'implies)
     (list 'or
           (list 'not (eliminate-implications (cadr expr)))
           (eliminate-implications (caddr expr))))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'iff)
     (let ((p (eliminate-implications (cadr expr)))
           (q (eliminate-implications (caddr expr))))
       (list 'and
             (list 'or (list 'not p) q)
             (list 'or (list 'not q) p))))
    ((eq? (car expr) 'not)
     (list 'not (eliminate-implications (cadr expr))))
    (else                                          ; and / or
     (list (car expr)
           (eliminate-implications (cadr expr))
           (eliminate-implications (caddr expr))))))
```

Implication becomes *not-P or Q*. Biconditional becomes the conjunction of
the two implications, each unfolded. And, or, and not recurse.

Phase two: push negations in.

```scheme
(define (push-negations expr)
  (cond
    ((symbol? expr) expr)
    ((eq? (car expr) 'not)
     (let ((inside (cadr expr)))
       (cond
         ((symbol? inside)                        ; not on atom: leave
          expr)
         ((eq? (car inside) 'not)                 ; double negation: cancel
          (push-negations (cadr inside)))
         ((eq? (car inside) 'and)                 ; not (A and B) => (not A) or (not B)
          (push-negations
            (list 'or
                  (list 'not (cadr inside))
                  (list 'not (caddr inside)))))
         ((eq? (car inside) 'or)                  ; not (A or B) => (not A) and (not B)
          (push-negations
            (list 'and
                  (list 'not (cadr inside))
                  (list 'not (caddr inside))))))))
    (else
     (list (car expr)
           (push-negations (cadr expr))
           (push-negations (caddr expr))))))
```

Two rules, both from De Morgan. Not-of-and becomes or-of-nots. Not-of-or
becomes and-of-nots. Plus a base case: not-of-not cancels. After running
this pass the formula has negations only sitting on atomic propositions.

Phase three is a small piece of algebra: distributing disjunction over
conjunction. I will spare you the full listing here; it is a mechanical
recursion that spots `(or A (and B C))` and rewrites it as
`(and (or A B) (or A C))`. Appendix D shows the whole pipeline running end
to end and hands the output to a DPLL solver.

## What propositional logic cannot do

Before we leave this chapter I want to make the ceiling of propositional
logic honest. Consider the sentence:

*Every prime greater than two is odd.*

You cannot say this in propositional logic. Not because it is complicated —
it is not — but because propositional logic has no way to talk about *every
prime*. It can only talk about specific claims. If you had a proposition
*Prime-3-is-odd* and another *Prime-5-is-odd* and another *Prime-7-is-odd*,
you could say each of them individually, but you could not generalize.

Or:

*There exists a witness such that the algorithm terminates.*

Again, propositional logic is silent. It cannot quantify. To say things like
*every* and *there exists*, we need predicate logic, which is what the
next chapter is about.

Propositional logic is nonetheless the correct starting point. Every richer
logic — predicate, modal, temporal, linear, categorical — is built by
adding features on top of the propositional core. The core does not change.
The core is: statements combine with connectives, valuations assign truth,
entailment is preservation across valuations. That is the whole game at
this level, and everything else in this book is layers of extra
scaffolding on that game.

## Variations to try

Rewrite `eval-prop` so it uses `match` instead of `cond`. The result should
be shorter and, in my opinion, clearer; the match arms line up beautifully
with the abstract-syntax cases.

Add an `nand` connective (*not both*). Extend the interpreter and the
`collect-atoms` walker. Verify that every formula in the original language
can be rewritten using only `nand` — this is the *functional completeness*
of NAND, a fact famously exploited in digital circuit design where every
gate is built from NAND gates alone.

Write a `simplify` pass that turns `(and P #t)` into `P`, `(or P #f)` into
`P`, `(and P P)` into `P`, and so on. Chain it after `push-negations` in the
CNF pipeline; the output formula will be dramatically smaller.

Instrument `entails?` to return not just a boolean but, when the answer is
`#f`, a *counterexample* — the valuation that satisfies all the premises
but fails the conclusion. This is the seed of what a proof assistant does
when a proof attempt fails. It is a very civilised way to be wrong: not
just *no* but *here is why*.

## Try this

Pick a piece of everyday reasoning. Not a mathematical one — a real one, out
of your day. *If it rains, the picnic is off. It is not raining. Therefore
the picnic is on.* Convert it to propositional form. Ask our checker
whether the reasoning is valid. Sit with the answer.

I will spoil the punchline: the checker will say *no*. This is the *denying
the antecedent* fallacy. Just because the antecedent of the implication
fails does not mean the conclusion fails. Maybe the picnic is off for other
reasons — the host is sick, the field is booked. The implication only tells
us what happens if it rains; it says nothing about what happens if it does
not.

Real reasoning, done in ordinary language, is riddled with fallacies of
this shape. That is not a failure of ordinary language; it is a design
feature. Ordinary language is fast and cheap. Formal logic is slow and
expensive. You use the formal machinery when you cannot afford to be
wrong.

## Closing

We built a propositional-logic interpreter in a few dozen lines of Scheme.
It evaluates formulas, enumerates truth tables, checks entailment, and
handles a slice of the normal-form machinery. It is a small thing, and it
would not surprise Enderton — the whole apparatus is in the first two
chapters of his textbook. What matters for us is that the whole apparatus
is *inside* Motoi Scheme now. We can reason about propositional formulas
by running programs. That is the pattern the rest of the book will follow.
Every logical system we meet from here on will be *built*, in code, that
you can run.

Next chapter: predicate logic. We add quantifiers, and the world of things
we can say opens up considerably.
"
